# virtualenvwrapper
mkvirtualenv env1
workon env1

# virtualenv + pip:
sudo easy_install pip
sudo easy_install virtualenv
* pip is purely for installing python packages; it is superior to easy_install 
* create virtualenvs to support multiple python / dependency versions

* note that your current virtualenv was installed with python 3(?) so:
    * virtualenv -p python3 env
* to make your virtualenv the default: source env/bin/activate
* record requirements for a given installation
    * pip freeze > requirements
    * later if needed pip install -r requirements.txt
* to run ipython and ipython notebook, ipython needs to be installed explicitly and then for nb so do a few support modules:
    * pyzmq and tornado (pip3 install ...)
Now>> cd insight; source env/bin/activate



to create a new virtualenv in folder ENV just type
$ virtualenv ENV
and then to activate it 
$ source ENV/bin/activate
